How Tarot Works

🌙 What is Tarot?

Tarot is a tool for reflection and self-discovery. Think of it as a mirror for your subconscious mind. The cards don't predict a fixed future. Instead, they reveal patterns, possibilities, and perspectives you might not have considered.

🃏 The Deck

A full tarot deck contains 78 cards divided into two groups:

Major Arcana (22 cards)

The "big picture" cards representing major life themes, spiritual lessons, and significant turning points. These are the famous cards like The Fool, Death, and The Tower.

Minor Arcana (56 cards)

The "everyday life" cards covering daily events, challenges, and interactions. Divided into four suits:

  • Wands (Fire): Passion, creativity, action, willpower
  • Cups (Water): Emotions, relationships, intuition, feelings
  • Swords (Air): Thoughts, communication, conflict, truth
  • Pentacles (Earth): Material world, money, health, work

Think of it this way: Major Arcana are the big plot points in your story, while Minor Arcana are the daily scenes that fill in the details.

🔮 How to Ask Questions

The quality of your reading depends on the quality of your question. Here's how to frame them:

✓ Good Questions (Open-Ended)

  • "What do I need to know about...?"
  • "What is blocking me from...?"
  • "How can I improve...?"
  • "What should I focus on regarding...?"
  • "What lesson is this situation teaching me?"
  • "What energy surrounds my...?"

✗ Questions to Avoid

  • Yes/no questions ("Will I get the job?")
  • Timing questions ("When will I meet someone?")
  • Questions about others' thoughts/feelings
  • Questions that remove your agency

🎴 How Many Cards to Pull

The number of cards you draw depends on what kind of insight you're looking for:

1 Card: Daily Guidance

Perfect for a quick daily check-in, simple questions, or when you need a single piece of advice. Great for beginners.

Use for: "What energy should I focus on today?" or "What do I need to know right now?"

2 Cards: Either/Or Decisions

Draw one card for each option you're considering. Compare the energies to see which path feels right.

Use for: "Should I take Job A or Job B?" or "Stay or go?"

3 Cards: Past, Present, Future

The most popular spread. First card shows what led to now, second shows the current situation, third shows where things are heading. Can also be read as Situation, Action, Outcome.

Use for: Any situation where you want the full picture and timeline.

4 Cards: Four Directions

A balanced view from all angles. Cards represent: (1) East/Air: thoughts and communication, (2) South/Fire: passion and action, (3) West/Water: emotions and intuition, (4) North/Earth: practical matters and grounding.

Use for: Getting a well-rounded perspective on any situation.

5 Cards: Cross Spread

A focused cross pattern. Cards represent: (1) Present situation, (2) Challenge or obstacle, (3) Past influences, (4) Future direction, (5) Potential outcome.

Use for: Complex situations that need deeper exploration.

6 Cards: Problem Solving

Structured guidance for decisions. Cards represent: (1) The problem, (2) What caused it, (3) What you can control, (4) What you cannot control, (5) What you need to accept, (6) The path forward.

Use for: Working through a specific challenge or obstacle.

7 Cards: Horseshoe Spread

A classic arc of insight. Cards represent: (1) Past, (2) Present, (3) Future, (4) Your approach/attitude, (5) External influences, (6) Hopes and fears, (7) Final outcome.

Use for: Major life decisions or comprehensive situation analysis.

8 Cards: Relationship Spread

Deep dive into connections. Cards represent: (1) You now, (2) The other person, (3) The connection between you, (4) Foundation of relationship, (5) Past influences, (6) What you want, (7) What they want, (8) Where this is heading.

Use for: Understanding any relationship (romantic, family, friendship, work).

9 Cards: Box Spread

A 3x3 grid for thorough analysis. Top row: past situation, present situation, future situation. Middle row: what helps you, the core issue, what blocks you. Bottom row: your foundation, advice, likely outcome.

Use for: When you need to see all dimensions of a complex matter.

10 Cards: Celtic Cross

The most famous and comprehensive spread. Cards represent: (1) Present, (2) Challenge/crossing, (3) Foundation, (4) Recent past, (5) Possible future, (6) Near future, (7) Your attitude, (8) Environment/others, (9) Hopes and fears, (10) Final outcome.

Use for: Major life questions, yearly reviews, or when you need the most complete picture possible.

Start with 1 or 3 cards until you get comfortable. More cards isn't always better. Sometimes a single card says everything you need to hear.

💫 Example Questions by Topic

Career

"What do I need to understand about my current career path?"

Relationships

"How can I bring more harmony to my relationships?"

Personal Growth

"What is holding me back from reaching my potential?"

Decisions

"What should I consider before making this choice?"

📖 How to Interpret Your Card

There's no single "right" way to read tarot. Here are different approaches:

1. First Impression

What's your gut reaction when you see the card? Your intuition often knows before your mind catches up.

2. Traditional Meaning

Read the provided meaning and keywords. How do they relate to your question or current situation?

3. Personal Association

What does the symbol remind YOU of? Personal connections often hold the deepest meaning.

4. Advice Perspective

If this card were giving you advice, what would it say? What action does it suggest?

5. Shadow Work

What uncomfortable truth might this card be pointing to? What are you avoiding?

🔄 Reversed Cards

When a card appears upside-down (reversed), it can mean:

  • Blocked energy: The card's theme is present but struggling to express
  • Internal focus: The energy is turned inward rather than outward
  • Opposite meaning: Sometimes the reversed meaning contrasts the upright
  • Delayed timing: The energy is coming, but not yet fully manifested

✨ Tips for Better Readings

  • Take a few deep breaths before drawing
  • Clear your mind and focus on your question
  • Don't keep drawing until you get a card you "like"
  • Journal your readings to track patterns over time
  • Remember: YOU have the power. The cards are just a tool

Moon Phases

🌕

Full Moon

100% illuminated

Day 15 of lunar cycle

Current Phase Energy

The Full Moon brings illumination and completion. This is a powerful time for manifestation, celebration, and releasing what no longer serves you.

Recommended Activities

  • Celebrate achievements and progress
  • Release what no longer serves you
  • Perform gratitude rituals
  • Charge crystals and tarot decks

What to Avoid

  • Starting brand new projects
  • Making impulsive decisions
  • Ignoring heightened emotions

Tarot Connection

The Moon (XVIII)

The Moon card resonates strongly during this phase. Trust your intuition, pay attention to dreams, and explore your subconscious mind.

Suggested Spreads for This Phase

Complete Moon Cycle Guide

The lunar cycle lasts approximately 29.5 days. Each phase carries unique energy for tarot readings and spiritual work.

🌑

New Moon

Days 0-1

Beginnings, Intentions, Seeds

The moon is invisible, representing the void before creation. This is the most powerful time for setting intentions and planting seeds for what you wish to manifest.

New startsIntention settingInner reflectionPlanning

Best readings: Goal setting, new beginnings, what to focus on this cycle

🌒

Waxing Crescent

Days 2-6

Hope, Intention, Commitment

A sliver of light appears. Energy begins building. This is the time to commit to your intentions and take the first small steps toward your goals.

First stepsCommitmentGathering resourcesFaith

Best readings: What obstacles may arise, how to stay committed, resources needed

🌓

First Quarter

Days 7-9

Action, Decision, Challenges

Half the moon is illuminated. This is a time of action and potential challenges. Obstacles may arise that test your commitment. Push through with determination.

Decision timeChallengesTaking actionCourage

Best readings: Overcoming obstacles, decision making, what action to take

🌔

Waxing Gibbous

Days 10-13

Refinement, Patience, Trust

The moon is almost full. Refine your approach, make adjustments, and trust the process. Your manifestation is developing beneath the surface.

Fine-tuningPatienceAnalysisPreparation

Best readings: What needs adjustment, how to refine your approach, patience guidance

🌕

Full Moon

Days 14-15

Illumination, Culmination, Release

Maximum illumination brings clarity and heightened emotions. Celebrate what you have manifested and release what no longer serves your highest good.

CelebrationReleaseClarityGratitude

Best readings: What to release, gratitude readings, clarity on situations

🌖

Waning Gibbous

Days 16-19

Gratitude, Sharing, Introspection

Light begins to decrease. Share what you have learned, express gratitude, and begin looking inward. This is the start of the release cycle.

GratitudeSharing wisdomTeachingReceiving

Best readings: Lessons learned, what to share with others, receiving guidance

🌗

Last Quarter

Days 20-22

Release, Forgiveness, Letting Go

Half the moon is again visible, but decreasing. This is a powerful time for breaking bad habits, forgiving, and releasing old patterns, relationships, or beliefs.

Letting goForgivenessBreaking habitsClearing

Best readings: What to release, forgiveness work, breaking patterns

🌘

Waning Crescent

Days 23-28

Rest, Surrender, Healing

The final sliver before darkness. Time to rest, recuperate, and surrender. Honor endings and prepare for the rebirth that comes with the new moon.

RestSurrenderHealingClosure

Best readings: What needs healing, surrender guidance, preparing for new cycle

Moon Rituals for Tarot Readers

🌑 New Moon Ritual

Cleanse your deck, set intentions for the coming cycle, and draw a card to guide your focus. Write down what you wish to manifest.

🌕 Full Moon Ritual

Place your deck under moonlight to charge. Do a release reading to identify what to let go. Burn or bury a written list of what you're releasing.

🌓 Quarter Moon Check-in

Draw a single card to check your progress. At First Quarter, assess obstacles. At Last Quarter, assess what to release.

📅 Monthly Moon Journal

Track your readings alongside moon phases. Over time, you may notice patterns in which cards appear during certain phases.

Zodiac & Tarot

♑

Capricorn Season

December 22 - January 19

Earth Sign | Cardinal Quality

Current Season Energy

Capricorn season emphasizes ambition, discipline, and practical achievement. Focus on long-term goals and building solid foundations.

Key Themes

AmbitionDisciplineStructureAchievement

Ruling Planet: Saturn

Body Area: Knees, bones, skin

Colors: Black, dark brown, charcoal gray

Associated Tarot Cards

Reading Tips for This Season

During Capricorn season, focus your readings on career, long-term goals, and practical matters. The energy supports structured approaches and building foundations.

  • Ask about career advancement and professional goals
  • Explore what structures need to be built or strengthened
  • Focus on practical, actionable guidance
  • Consider readings about authority figures or mentors

All Zodiac Signs & Their Cards

Each zodiac sign is associated with specific Major Arcana cards. Understanding these connections deepens your tarot practice.

Elements: Zodiac & Tarot Suits

The four elements connect zodiac signs to tarot suits, creating a unified system of correspondence.

🔥

Fire

Masculine, Active, Yang

♈ Aries ♌ Leo ♐ Sagittarius

Suit of Wands

Fire represents passion, creativity, willpower, and spiritual energy. Fire signs are enthusiastic, dynamic, and action-oriented. In tarot, Wands deal with inspiration, ambition, and the spark of life.

PassionCreativityActionWillEnergyInspiration
💧

Water

Feminine, Receptive, Yin

♋ Cancer ♏ Scorpio ♓ Pisces

Suit of Cups

Water represents emotions, intuition, relationships, and the subconscious. Water signs are sensitive, empathetic, and deeply feeling. In tarot, Cups deal with love, feelings, and emotional connections.

EmotionsIntuitionLoveDreamsHealingCompassion
💨

Air

Masculine, Active, Yang

♊ Gemini ♎ Libra ♒ Aquarius

Suit of Swords

Air represents intellect, communication, truth, and the mind. Air signs are analytical, social, and idea-oriented. In tarot, Swords deal with thoughts, conflicts, decisions, and mental challenges.

IntellectCommunicationTruthLogicIdeasClarity
🌍

Earth

Feminine, Receptive, Yin

♉ Taurus ♍ Virgo ♑ Capricorn

Suit of Pentacles

Earth represents the material world, stability, health, and practical matters. Earth signs are grounded, reliable, and sensory-focused. In tarot, Pentacles deal with money, work, body, and physical reality.

MaterialStabilityHealthWealthNaturePatience

2. Taurus Money, possessions, values

7. Libra Partnerships, marriage, contracts
8. Scorpio Transformation, shared resources, intimacy

10. Capricorn Career, reputation, public life
